    "summary": "The Battle of Lake Trasimene (217 BC) was Hannibal's second major victory in Italy during the [[event:1054|Second Punic War]], an ambush on the shores of Lake Trasimene in Etruria that destroyed a Roman army of around 30,000 under the consul Gaius Flaminius. It remains one of history's largest military ambushes.\n\nHannibal deliberately left a gap in his route that invited Flaminius to pursue, then positioned his entire army — infantry concealed in hills to the north, cavalry blocking escape to the east — around a narrow strip of lakeshore. When the Roman army marched in at dawn in foggy conditions, they were surrounded and attacked from all sides simultaneously. Flaminius was killed in the fighting; roughly 15,000 Romans were killed and most of the remainder captured, many drowning in the lake. A relief force sent forward was also intercepted and destroyed. The battle so shocked Rome that the Senate appointed a dictator — Quintus Fabius Maximus — who began the strategy of avoiding pitched battle that eventually wore Hannibal down despite the disaster at [[event:1056|Battle of Cannae]] that followed.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Lake_Trasimene",
